"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:3.20.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">3.20.1</span> Pavement, The Pavement</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">לְבֵנָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(lvenah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod24:10\">EXO 24:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מַלְבֵּן</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(malben)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer43:9\">JER 43:9</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">רִצְפָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(ritsfah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr7:3\">2CH 7:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Esth1:6\">EST 1:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:17\">EZK 40:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:17\">EZK 40:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:18\">EZK 40:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:18\">EZK 40:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek42:3\">EZK 42:3</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">λιθόστρωτον</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(lithostrōton)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:13\">JHN 19:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">ἔδαφος</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(edafos)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir11:5\">SIR 11:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir20:18\">SIR 20:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Bel1:19\">BEL 1:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/3Macc2:22\">3MA 2:22</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/4Macc6:7\">4MA 6:7</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0437_pavement_roman_petra.jpg\" alt=\"Roman pavement, Petra\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Roman pavement, Petra (© High Contrast, CC BY 3.0 DE, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Pavement was an area paved with flat blocks of stone to form a courtyard (not a road). “The Pavement” was the name given to the inner courtyard of the Roman fortress of Antonia, which bordered the northwest corner of the Temple complex in Jerusalem.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer43:9\">JER 43:9</a>: The Hebrew word <em>malben</em> occurs elsewhere with the meaning of “brick mold” or “brickkiln” (see the discussion and references at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.8.1 Brick mold, brickkiln&lt;REALIA:1.8.1&gt;</a>). Here it seems to indicate the material from which the pavement is made; <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>, and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> all render it “brick pavement.” Jeremiah is told to hide the stones “in the <em>melet</em> of the <em>malben</em>.” The Hebrew word <em>melet</em> occurs only here, and its meaning is uncertain. Translations usually render it as some material in which the bricks would be set, for example, “clay” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Revised Standard Version (1989)\">NRSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>), “mortar” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>), or “cement” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr>). <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> avoids finding a specific material and focuses instead on the location, saying “underneath the brick pavement.”</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John19:13\">JHN 19:13</a>: In some languages translators may render “The Pavement” as “the court covered with large blocks of flat stone” or “the stone-paved courtyard.”</p>\n<p>The Greek word <em>edafos</em> does not refer to a specific place or even to a particular kind of construction. Thus it may be translated with a generic term such as “floor” or even “ground.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
